      <h1>Frenchiest French Toast Recipe</h1>
      <p>If <i lang="fr">oui</i> is the only French word you know, this French toast recipe will have you doing a lot of <i lang="fr">oui</i>-ing! Using the right ingredients will give you a velvety batter that will <em>coat</em> instead of <em>soak</em> your bread slices, leading to delight in bite after bite. Well, without further ado, shall <i lang="fr">oui</i>?</p>
      <h2>Ingredients (makes about 6 pieces)</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>4 eggs (I suppose you could use less if you don't like the taste of egg in your french toast)</li>
          <li>&frac12; cup heavy whipping cream (&frac14; milk if you haven't started keeping a stash of heavy in your fridge)</li>
          <li>1 tsp vanilla extract</li>
          <li>&frac12; ground cinnamon (Ceylon cinnamon kicks it up a notch)</li>
          <li>&frac14; ground nutmeg</li>
          <li>2 tbsp brown sugar</li>
          <li>a pinch of salt</li>
          <li>&frac14; c flour (Secret ingredient! Makes it less absorbable, aka no soggy toasts)</li>
          <li>Last, but not least, 6 slices of bread (Challah, brioche, Texas toast, or other thick-sliced bread)</li>
          <li>4 tbsp butter</li>
          <li>Powedered sugar for dusting</li>    
        </ul>
        <h2>Instructions</h2>
          <ol>
            <li>(Optional) Let your bread sit out for 24 hours. It'll add a great texture to guard against soggying up!</li>
            <li>In a shallow dish (8x8 inch pan, for example) whisk together the eggs heavy whipping cream, vanilla, cinnamon, nutmeg, brown sugar, and flour.</li>
            <li>Melt butter on griddle over medium heat. Cook for a good 2-3 minutes, then flip. Check to see if it's got the right browning you like to see on your french toast. Adjust if needed.</li>
            <li>(Optional) Dust finished slices with powdered sugar.</li>
          </ol>
